03788nam a22005415i 9780520969995DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20182018cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209699957 a10.1515/97805209699952doi  a(DE-B1597)519980  a(OCoLC)1022991171  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aQP255b.W28 2018 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a362.17/8309512231 aWahlberg, Ayo, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGood Quality :bThe Routinization of Sperm Banking in China /cAyo Wahlberg. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (248 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tList of Abbreviations -- tIntroduction: Sperm Crisis -- t1. The Birth of Assisted Reproductive Technology in China -- t2. Improving Population Quality -- t3. Exposed Biologies -- t4. Mobilizing Sperm Donors -- t5. Making Quality Auditable -- t6. Borrowing Sperm -- tConclusion: Routinization -- tCoda -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom its crude and uneasy beginnings thirty years ago, Chinese sperm banking has become a routine part of China’s pervasive and restrictive reproductive complex. Today, there are sperm banks in each of China’s twenty-two provinces, the biggest of which screen some three thousand to four thousand potential donors each year. Given the estimated one to two million azoospermic men--those who are unable to produce their own sperm--the demand remains insatiable. China’s twenty-two sperm banks cannot keep up, spurring sperm bank directors to publicly lament chronic shortages and even warn of a national ‘sperm crisis’ (jingzi weiji). Good Quality explores the issues behind the crisis, including declining sperm quality in the country due to environmental pollution, as well as a chronic national shortage of donors. In doing so, Wahlberg outlines the specific style of Chinese sperm banking that has emerged, shaped by the particular cultural, juridical, economic and social configurations that make up China’s restrictive reproductive complex. Good Quality shows how this high-throughput style shapes the ways in which men experience donation and how sperm is made available to couples who can afford it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArtificial inseminationzChina. 0aSperm bankszChina. 0aSperm banks. 0aSperm donorszChina. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311066767740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780520969995?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520969995423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520969995/original  a978-3-11-066767-7  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles